\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 <$Scr_Ps::0>}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab The Sand is webbed by a network of byways that are hardly there at all. They\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re not well traveled, and most are so windswept that footprints get filled back up with sand as soon as they\u8217\'92ve been made. These roads are only distinguished from the desert landscape by a series of five-ton waystones that stick up three meters out of the ground. If those gleaming white beams of rock weren\u8217\'92t there every league or so, you\u8217\'92d never know that under your feet was an ancient Jandrian route. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Pilgrims call them Charnel Roads because unlike the highways which keep to the river banks or hop between oases, these roads cut through the vast shadeless expanse of the Sand. Travelers get exposed to the sun, the wind, and the glare of the desert. The longer the road the deadlier it all is, though that\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s just a rule of thumb because the worst Charnel Road, the Bazul Road, is one of the shortest. It sits just north of Uncharted Portion where an ancient mountain range once stood. An eon of blasting sand had reduced those mountains to a rolling line of graveled hills, flat enough for the Bazul Road to snake up and down them, and to lead pilgrims to the greater shrine of Bazul. It only takes a full day to make the road if you start at the nearest Imperial outpost at Shahiz, but its such a difficult hike, and Pilgrims sweat so much from just the effort that the heat on top of it is unbearable. And it\u8217\'92s a saturating heat, too, because the chalky gravel underfoot is white as bone so it throws the sunlight right back up into the face. You get baked from below as much as from above. Can\u8217\'92t even hide in your own shadow.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0  \tab There is some shade on route: a little wood-frame waystation at a saddlepoint. The monks of Bazul keep it stocked with a cache of water buried in jugs. Some pilgrims sleep there in the day and make the road at night, skipping the sun altogether, but Solitant pilgrims don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t use it. They don\u8217\'92t trivialize the journey. They set out for the shrine in the morning and trudge through the brunt of it at midday. They do it, they say, because if Bazul did not intend for them to suffer, he would have set his earthly dwelling down on some oated knoll at the mouth of a Jeketian inlet. No, Bazul\u8217\'92s road was there in the Sand because Bazul put it there, and to skip this test of faith against flesh is to have no faith at all. This is the first lesson the road teaches the Solitant: the greatest temptation one must fight is the temptation to not try at all.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Once a pilgrim actually gets on the road the temptations start to give way to the struggle. There are still a few urges to deal with, a few spiritual lessons learn. For example, there\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s urge to stop and sit, to rest. Anywhere else in the world it would be a fine thing to do, but sitting down on a Charnel Road without shade is a mistake because the sun still bakes you even if you\u8217\'92re not moving. It will bake you tomorrow, too, so don\u8217\'92t saddle tomorrow\u8217\'92s self with today\u8217\'92s journey.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Solitants savor this particular ordeal because it highlights two important lessons: doom finds you much quicker than death, and doing nothing is the same as doing the wrong thing. Nowhere else in the world are these principles so clear. Out on a Charnel Road, a man, sitting down, with no aches or pains and a full waterskin, is still moving towards the point of no return. This is the the inescapable consequence of Time: inaction is action itself, and for the Solitant, it is a refusal of the Divine gift of Will. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab It is important to note that the Solitant word for doomed is \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91Shiskason\u8217\'92, and it doesn\u8217\'92t mean \u8216\'91doomed\u8217\'92 exactly. Unlike \u8216\'91doomed\u8217\'92 it carries an air of blame, not fate. It reads roughly like, \u8216\'91thing-that-you-did-not-prevent\u8217\'92. This gets to the heart of the Solitant religion: all creatures are naturally immortal, but every creature dies because every uncouth mistake ages the soul, every missed opportunity for righteousness draws another line in the face. If only people made the right decisions at every step they would live forever, but we\u8217\'92re all too ignorant, too dumb, and too lazy, so the weight of our failures literally kill us. Here, a pilgrim becomes a Shiska for no other reason than he stopped and he sat and he did not walk the road.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab  This cosmology is woven into the Solitant\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s yellow haircloth habit. The constant itch is a constant reminder to never waste time. It keeps one alert and attentive to even the smallest opportunity to exercise Will. Of course, this creates another temptation pilgrims must fight on the Charnel Roads: the temptation to cast the scratchy habit aside. Not only does it itch, but the heat gets underneath it. The urge to take it off, to get the heat out and let the sweaty skin breathe is ever present. It\u8217\'92s here that the body starts to bargain with the mind, \u8220\'93Just take it off for a little while,\u8221\'94 it pleads. \u8220\'93No one is watching. No one would know.\u8221\'94 Pilgrims don\u8217\'92t ever do it, though. It\u8217\'92s a familiar temptation. Not only would they be casting aside their symbol of devotion, they\u8217\'92d actually be making it easer for the sun to sap their bodies of moisture and energy. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Its not the temptations, its the physical struggle that does most pilgrims in. On the Bazul road a twisted ankle or a tweaked knee is all but inevitable. Man\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s upright gait just isn\u8217\'92t designed for a sustained trudge uphill through loosely packed gravel. No pilgrim has ever made the journey without stumbling a time or two, and when they fall their hands and feet get cut because the gravel isn\u8217\'92t smooth like riverstone, it\u8217\'92s been chipped unevenly by the wind and the sand. It\u8217\'92s got points and edges, some as sharp as blades.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Solitant monks are used to fighting through physical pain, but nonetheless, it slows them down and gives the sun time to work delirium into them. At that point if they make a mistake with water, they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92re dead, and it\u8217\'92s an easy mistake to make for any Solitants that come from across the northern sea. They don\u8217\'92t know what the sun can do to a body with just a few hours. When these foreigners come to the Bazul Road, all they hear is that its only a days journey. }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 One}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  day\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s journey. }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 Only}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  twenty leagues. Sure, they hear stories about the deaths, but they shrug them off because such stories are never accurate. Carnage is always embellished. Three water-skins }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1 should}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  be enough. }
\par\pard\plain \fi706\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab It\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s hard to get experience traveling in the Sand, because getting experience means you\u8217\'92ve got to survive your mistakes. The first time a person pricks her water-skin on the half-buried thorn of a karkel-bush seed pod is the last time. There\u8217\'92s just no room for error, and dying in the Sand isn\u8217\'92t a pleasant way to go. If the heat takes you quick its not so bad, but if it doesn\u8217\'92t, if you\u8217\'92ve rationed water well enough to die slowly, then your mouth dries out and your tongue swells up and your eyes lose their moisture and start to scratch. Then a thumping nausea works its way out from your head and into your stomach and then into your marrow\u8217\'92s jelly. It\u8217\'92s no coincidence that almost every corpse found on a Charnel Road is found curled up like fetus against the agony, though not many corpses are found because a pack of lizards can eat a full adult male in a just few hands, and when you\u8217\'92re dying of thirst, weak as a babe, you might still be alive when they do it.}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Shade giving trees  they don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t like. Kills them. Fall asleep under it and you don\u8217\'92t wake up. They think they\u8217\'92re killers. We keep them up because they keep scandri away. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93They aren\u8217\'92t coming. Too many kekle trees.\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 <!$Scr_Ps::0>}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What\u8217\'92s wrong with kackle trees?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93They\u8217\'92re shade giving trees. They\u8217\'92re afraid them.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Trees don\u8217\'92t have souls. Trees aren\u8217\'92t even living things.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Dan gives Ralph a look.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93If you call it life,\u8221\'94 Ralph continued, \u8220\'93it\u8217\'92s gotta be killing something, doesn\u8217\'92t it? Anything can die. I can crush a rock with my hammer and I can crush a bug with my hammer, yet we say the rock is a thing and the bug is a life. Why? Because the bug kills other bugs. That\u8217\'92s how you know they\u8217\'92re alive. It\u8217\'92s the killing and the eating.\u8221\'94 That last word rolled through Ralph\u8217\'92s beard like a saw.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What about children?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Trees eat children?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Fuck, no\u8230\'85 Definition of life. Bugs have children, rocks don\u8217\'92t. That\u8217\'92s what makes a bug alive.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Cut a man\u8217\'92s balls off, what is he then? Dead? Just because he can\u8217\'92t have children?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93He\u8217\'92s of a type that has children.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Ralph just shrugged. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I say it\u8217\'92s killing. If these trees are alive, then that means they\u8217\'92re killing something. Could be it\u8217\'92s us. I heard once that we\u8217\'92re supposed to be immortal, and that the trees are poisoning the air to age us, so they can feast on our corpses when we die. We think we\u8217\'92re tending the orchard field but it\u8217\'92s really the orchard field tending to us!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Where the hell did you hear that?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93From some pacified herd in the south. They\u8217\'92re mostly dead now. Dog worshippers the were. Fed their dead to packs of dogs to keep them out of the ground. Ground the bones to dust then tossed in with the water the dogs lapped up. Then they made bricks out of the feces.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93No wonder you\u8217\'92re all \u8230\'85\u8221\'94 Loopey}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92ve always said I should contemplate more, so I\u8217\'92ve been contemplating. What do you think Eliza?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Living things can grow. Everything else can only waste away.\u8221\'94}
